      "hints": [
        "Outer derivative (at inner) times inner derivative.",
        "$f'(g(x)) g'(x)$."
      ],
      "explanation": "Chain rule: $(f \\circ g)'(x) = f'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x)$.",
      "steps": [
        "**Chain rule formula:** $\\dfrac{d}{dx}[f(g(x))] = f'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x)$.",
        "**Mantra: 'derivative of the outer (leaving the inner intact) times derivative of the inner'.**",
        "**When you use it.** Any time you see a function INSIDE another — like $\\sin(x^2)$, $e^{3x}$, $(2x+1)^5$, $\\sqrt{x^2+1}$. These are COMPOSITIONS and the chain rule unwraps them.",
        "**The hardest part is identifying outer vs inner.** Outer = what you'd compute LAST if calculating the function value. Inner = what you'd compute FIRST. For $\\sin(x^2)$: square first, then take sine — so $\\sin$ is the outer.",
        "**Why the formula has this shape.** Differentiating a composition propagates the chain of changes: a small change in $x$ becomes a small change in $g(x)$ (rate $g'$), which becomes a small change in $f(g(x))$ (rate $f'$ at that point). Multiply rates."
      ],
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
